  <!-- WIRRAL PROPERTY KNOWLEDGE — UNIQUE SECTION -->
  <section class="pf-section" style="background:#f1f5f9;">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="pf-section-label">WIRRAL LOCAL KNOWLEDGE</span>
      <h2>Your Wirral Property. What Your Annual Service Covers That Others Miss.</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">The Wirral's housing diversity is exceptional. A Victorian Birkenhead terrace with a 15-year-old regular boiler has completely different service priorities to a coastal West Kirby property or a large Heswall system boiler. Our engineers service every configuration.</p>

      <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr;gap:1.5rem;margin-top:2rem;">

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <div style="display:flex;gap:1rem;align-items:flex-start;flex-wrap:wrap;">
            <div style="background:var(--orange);color:#fff;border-radius:6px;padding:0.3rem 0.75rem;font-family:'Barlow Condensed',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:0.85rem;white-space:nowrap;flex-shrink:0;">CH41 CH42 CH44</div>
            <div>
              <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Birkenhead, Wallasey and Rock Ferry. Older Boilers, Critical Heat Exchanger Checks.</strong>
              <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">The high density of pre-2005 boilers in CH41, CH42 and CH44 means heat exchanger condition is the primary service priority. Older heat exchangers develop micro-cracks and corrosion that initially have no visible symptoms but reduce combustion efficiency and create early-stage carbon monoxide risk. Our service includes a thorough combustion gas analysis that identifies whether the heat exchanger is maintaining correct gas-to-air ratios. We also check original flue runs in these properties, which in many Birkenhead terraces were installed in the 1990s and may have seal degradation that has gone undetected.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <div style="display:flex;gap:1rem;align-items:flex-start;flex-wrap:wrap;">
            <div style="background:var(--orange);color:#fff;border-radius:6px;padding:0.3rem 0.75rem;font-family:'Barlow Condensed',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:0.85rem;white-space:nowrap;flex-shrink:0;">CH47 CH48</div>
            <div>
              <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Hoylake and West Kirby. Salt Air and External Flue Condition.</strong>
              <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Coastal properties in Hoylake and West Kirby face salt-laden air from the Irish Sea that accelerates corrosion on external components. At every annual service in these areas, we specifically check the external flue terminal for corrosion and blockage, check any external overflow pipes and condensate discharge routes, and inspect the boiler casing seals where wall-mounted units are on external elevations. These are checks that engineers without coastal experience often overlook. The boiler itself may be working perfectly but an external flue terminal that has corroded can both restrict airflow and create a carbon monoxide risk.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <div style="display:flex;gap:1rem;align-items:flex-start;flex-wrap:wrap;">
            <div style="background:var(--orange);color:#fff;border-radius:6px;padding:0.3rem 0.75rem;font-family:'Barlow Condensed',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:0.85rem;white-space:nowrap;flex-shrink:0;">CH60 CH61 CH64</div>
            <div>
              <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Heswall, Pensby and Neston. System Boiler Services Are Not Combi Services.</strong>
              <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">The larger properties in south Wirral frequently have system boilers paired with hot water cylinders, multi-zone heating and underfloor circuits. A system boiler annual service includes everything a combi service covers, plus zone valve testing and operation, pump condition assessment, expansion vessel pressure check, cylinder thermostat and immersion check, and motorised valve function. This takes more time than a standard combi service. We allow for this in our appointments and charge the same £120 — we do not add a surcharge for system boiler complexity that many engineers add quietly. We also carry zone valve and pump spares on every Wirral van so minor faults can be addressed immediately.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <div style="display:flex;gap:1rem;align-items:flex-start;flex-wrap:wrap;">
            <div style="background:var(--orange);color:#fff;border-radius:6px;padding:0.3rem 0.75rem;font-family:'Barlow Condensed',sans-serif;font-weight:900;font-size:0.85rem;white-space:nowrap;flex-shrink:0;">CH43 CH46 CH62 CH63</div>
            <div>
              <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Prenton, Moreton, Bebington and Bromborough. Standard Combi Stock, Inhibitor Priority.</strong>
              <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">The large stock of 1980s to 2010s semi-detached properties across central and south Wirral is predominantly on combi boilers installed in the last 10 to 20 years. For these properties, inhibitor concentration is typically the most important annual check. Inhibitor degrades year on year and falls below effective concentration — at which point sludge and magnetite build-up begins in the heat exchanger and radiators. We test inhibitor concentration on every service and top up to the correct level as standard. Many services from cheaper engineers in these areas skip this step because it takes time and adds marginal cost. We include it without exception.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
